#. type: Title #
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:10
#, no-wrap
msgid "Using `rsync` To Keep Two Machines Synchronized"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:15
msgid "This is everything you'll need to understand and follow along with this guide."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:23
msgid "A machine running Rocky Linux."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:23
msgid "To be comfortable with modifying configuration files from the command-line."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:23
msgid "Knowledge of how to use a command line editor (we use _vi_ here, but you could use your favorite editor)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:23
msgid "You will need root access, and ideally be signed in as the root user in your terminal."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:23
msgid "Public and Private SSH key pairs."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:23
msgid "Able to create a simple bash script, using vi or your favorite editor, and test it."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:23
msgid "Able to use _crontab_ to automate the running of the script."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:27
msgid "Using `rsync` over SSH is neither as powerful as [lsyncd](../backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md) (which allows you to watch a directory or file for changes and keep it synchronized in real time), or as flexible as [rsnapshot](../backup/rsnapshot_backup.md) (which offers the ability to easily backup multiple targets from a single machine). However, it does provide the ability to keep two computers up to date on a schedule that you define."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:29
msgid "If you need to keep a set of directories on the target computer up to date, and you don't care about real-time synchronization as a feature, then `rsync` over SSH is probably the best solution."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:31
msgid "For all of the below, we will be doing things as the root user, so either login as root or use the `sudo -s` command to switch to the root user in your terminal."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:32
#, no-wrap
msgid "Installing `rsync`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:35
msgid "Although `rsync` may already be installed, it is best to update `rsync` to the latest version on the source and target computers. To ensure that `rsync` is installed and up to date, do the following on both computers:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:37
msgid "`dnf install rsync`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:39
msgid "If the package is not installed, `dnf` will ask you to confirm the installation, if it is already installed, `dnf` will look for an update and prompt to install it."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:40
#, no-wrap
msgid "Preparing The Environment"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:43
msgid "This particular example will use `rsync` on the target machine to pull from the source instead of pushing from the source to the target, so you need to set up an [SSH key pair](../security/ssh_public_private_keys.md) for this . Once the SSH key pair has been created and password-free access from the target computer to the source computer has been confirmed, you can start."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:44
#, no-wrap
msgid "`rsync` Parameters And Setting Up A Script"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:47
msgid "Before we get terribly carried away with setting up a script, we first need to decide what parameters we want to use with `rsync`. There are many possibilities, so take a look at the [manual for rsync](https://linux.die.net/man/1/rsync). The most common way to use `rsync` is to use the `-a` option, because `-a`, or archive, combines a number of options into one and these are very common options. What does -a include?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:55
msgid "-r, recurse the directories"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:55
msgid "-l, maintain symbolic links as symbolic links"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:55
msgid "-p, preserve permissions"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:55
msgid "-t, preserve modification times"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:55
msgid "-g, preserve group-"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:55
msgid "-o, preserve owner"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:55
msgid "-D, preserve device files"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:57
msgid "The only other options that we need to specify in this example is:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:60
msgid "-e, specify the remote shell to use"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:60
msgid "--delete, which says if the target directory has a file in it that doesn't exist on the source, get rid of it"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:62
msgid "Next, we need to set up a script by creating a file for it (again, use your favorite editor if you are not familiar with vi). To create the file, just use this command:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:64
msgid "`vi /usr/local/sbin/rsync_dirs`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:66
msgid "And then make it executable:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:68
msgid "`chmod +x /usr/local/sbin/rsync_dirs`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:69
#, no-wrap
msgid "Testing"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:72
msgid "Now, scripting makes it super simple and safe so that you can test it fearlessly. Please note that the URL used below is \"source.domain.com\". Replace it with the domain or IP address of your own source computer, both will work. Also remember that in this example, the script is created on the \"target\" computer, because the file is pulled from the source computer:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:73
#, no-wrap
msgid "#!/bin/bash\n"
"/usr/bin/rsync -ae ssh --delete root@source.domain.com:/home/your_user /home\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:81
#, no-wrap
msgid "    In this case, we assume that your home directory does not exist on the target machine. **If it exists, you may want to back it up before executing the script!**\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:83
msgid "Now run the script:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:85
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:95
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:103
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:113
msgid "`/usr/local/sbin/rsync_dirs`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:87
msgid "If all is well, you should get a completely synchronized copy of your home directory on the target machine. Check to be sure this is the case."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:89
msgid "Assuming all of that worked out as we hoped, go ahead and create a new file on the source machine in your home directory:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:91
msgid "`touch /home/your_user/testfile.txt`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:93
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:101
msgid "Run the script again:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:97
msgid "Then verify that the target computer receives the new file. If so, the next step is to check the deletion process. Delete the file we just created on the source computer:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:99
msgid "`rm -f /home/your_user/testfile.txt`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:105
msgid "Verify that the file no longer exists on the target computer."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:107
msgid "Finally, let's create a file on the target machine that doesn't exist on the source. So, on the target:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:109
msgid "`touch /home/your_user/a_different_file.txt`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:111
msgid "Run the script a final time:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:115
msgid "The file we just created on the target should now be gone, because it does not exist on the source."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:117
msgid "Assuming all of this worked as expected, go ahead and modify the script to synchronize all the directories that you want."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:118
#, no-wrap
msgid "Automating Everything"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:121
msgid "We may not want to manually run this script every time we want to synchronize, so the next step is to do this automatically. Suppose you want to run this script at 11 PM every night. To automate this, use crontab:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:125
msgid "This will pull up the cron, which may look something like this:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block (bash)
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:126
#, no-wrap
msgid "# Edit this file to introduce tasks to be run by cron.\n"
"#\n"
"# Each task to run has to be defined through a single line\n"
"# indicating with different fields when the task will be run\n"
"# and what command to run for the task\n"
"#\n"
"# To define the time you can provide concrete values for\n"
"# minute (m), hour (h), day of month (dom), month (mon),\n"
"# and day of week (dow) or use '*' in these fields (for 'any').\n"
"#\n"
"# Notice that tasks will be started based on the cron's system\n"
"# daemon's notion of time and timezones.\n"
"#\n"
"# Output of the crontab jobs (including errors) is sent through\n"
"# email to the user the crontab file belongs to (unless redirected).\n"
"#\n"
"# For example, you can run a backup of all your user accounts\n"
"# at 5 a.m every week with:\n"
"# 0 5 * * 1 tar -zcf /var/backups/home.tgz /home/\n"
"#\n"
"# For more information see the manual pages of crontab(5) and cron(8)\n"
"#\n"
"# m h  dom mon dow   command\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:152
msgid "The cron is set up on a 24-hour clock, so what we will need for our entry at the bottom of this file is:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:154
#, no-wrap
msgid "`00 23   *  *  *    /usr/local/sbin/rsync_dirs`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:156
msgid "What this says is to run this command at 00 minute, 23 h, every day, every month, and every day of the week. Save your cron entry with:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:158
msgid "`Shift : wq!`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:160
msgid "... or with the commands that your favorite editor uses for saving a file."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/rsync_ssh.md:163
msgid "Although `rsync` is not as flexible or powerful as other tools, it provides simple file synchronization, which is always useful."
msgstr ""

